<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-912-522  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 912 522.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>EDN  Nov 9 1989 v34 n23 p201(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Resonant-mode design techniques improve switcher performance.andO;(Designer's Guide: Resonant-Mode Power Supplies: Part 1)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Sykes, Frederick E.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Resonant-mode power supplies operate at higher switchingfrequencies than PWM designs, which lets smaller transformer andoutput-filter components be used.andP;  Use of sine-wave current andvoltages in resonant mode cuts switching losses, EMI and componentstresses; implementation of resonant-mode design is facilitated bythe availability of dedicated resonant-mode control ICs.andP;  The mostcommon type of resonant-mode supplies have the central componentsof PWM designs but add a resonant inductor and resonant capacitor,which are used to attain lossless switching by shaping the voltageand current of the transformer.andP;  Whereas PWM designs regulateoutputs by fixing the control frequency and varying the on time ofthe power switches, resonant-mode designs vary the switchingfrequency and fix the on or off times of the power switches.andP;  Theadvantages of resonant-mode design are described.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Power SupplyCircuit DesignNew TechniqueVoltage RegulatorsSwitchesIntegrated circuits.andO;Feature:   illustrationchart.andO;Caption:   Resonant-mode circuits differ from PWM. (chart)Resonant-mode topologies fall into two basic groups. (chart)Half-bridge resonant-converter waveforms show current, voltage,control. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>